                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">A. Hancock 1849.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4838.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1854): </ref>538–9.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD was apparently beginning to suspect that <hi rend="italic">Alcippe</hi>, like <hi rend="italic">Ibla</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Scalpellum</hi>, was not hermaphrodite. He found no external male organs in his specimens and also discovered that each had minute parasites attached to them. See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4838.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1854): </ref>555.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1500.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Albany Hancock, 10 February [1853]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Arthrobalanus (<hi rend="italic">Cryptophialus minutus</hi>). CD had long believed that <hi rend="italic">Alcippe</hi> and Arthrobalanus were allied owing to the similarity in the number and position of their cirri and in their habits (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1506.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Collected papers</hi></ref> 1: 250 and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 4, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1253.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Albany Hancock, [21 September 1849]</ref>). Because of this belief he had deferred examining <hi rend="italic">Alcippe</hi> until he was finished with the common cirripedes. For a discussion of their differences, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4838.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1854): </ref>563–6.</note>
        </div>        
            
